If the user can't be found by oslogin, then we should return SUCCESS to avoid preventing a local user from logging in. We could return DENIED on a server failure, but then this would then also block local users in the event of a backend failure. Returning SUCCESS ensures we don't impact a local user's ability to log in, but DENIED would definitely be more secure, so I can see value in both choices. This behavior also only applies to the user lookup--if we fail the authorize call at any point, that will always result in DENIED. 

The risk would be if that exact call failed, the similar lookup in the auth_keys command would also have to fail(and the user also has to have local ssh keys), and all other lookups succeeded, we may accidentally permit a user who shouldn't log in. A persistent backend failure would mean other user lookups would fail, and nss would also not be able to get the user's info, so it is unlikely we would even get this far.

@illfelder any preference on what we should do?

@mikethebeer I think that we need also a way to provide a password if we execute an sql stmt with `crash -U -c <stmt>`. psql uses the `~/.pgpass` but also an env variable `PGPASSWORD`.  Check: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/6405127/how-do-i-specify-a-password-to-psql-non-interactively/6405162
If we don't have something like that then a user which is authenticated with password cannot execute crash -c ...

